Here's a basic example of a media query for mobile devices:

```
@media only screen and (max-width: 767px) {
  /* styles for mobile devices go here */
}
```

However, this will only match devices with a maximum screen width of 767px, and may not account for the different aspect ratios and screen densities of mobile devices. 

To better target mobile devices, you can use the following media queries, which also account for different screen densities and aspect ratios:

```
/* Mobile devices ( portrait orientation) */
@media only screen and (max-width: 480px) {
  /* styles for mobile devices go here */
}

/* Mobile devices ( landscape orientation) */
@media only screen and (min-width: 481px) and (max-width: 1023px) {
  /* styles for mobile devices in landscape orientation go here */
}

/* Mobile devices (very wide screens) */
@media only screen and (min-width: 1024px) and (max-width: 768px) {
  /* styles for mobile devices in very wide screens go here */
}

/* Mobile devices (extra wide screens) */
@media only screen and (min-width: 769px) {
  /* styles for mobile devices in extra wide screens go here */
}
```

Alternatively, you can use the following media query to target mobile devices across all screen orientations and densities:

```
@media only screen and (max-width: 1024px) {
  /* styles for mobile devices go here */
}
```

This media query will match devices with a maximum screen width of 1024px, regardless of their aspect ratio or screen density.

