Here's a basic media query for mobile devices:

```css
/* Mobile devices (phones) - 768px and below */
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  /* Your mobile styles here */
  body {
    font-size: 16px;
    padding: 10px;
  }

  .container {
    width: 100%;
    margin: 0;
  }

  .nav-menu {
    display: none; /* Hide desktop navigation */
  }

  .mobile-menu {
    display: block; /* Show mobile menu */
  }
}
```

Here are some common mobile breakpoints you can use:

```css
/* Extra small devices (phones, 600px and down) */
@media only screen and (max-width: 600px) {
  /* Styles for very small phones */
}

/* Small devices (portrait tablets and large phones, 768px and down) */
@media only screen and (max-width: 768px) {
  /* Styles for phones and small tablets */
}

/* More specific mobile-first approach */
@media screen and (min-width: 320px) and (max-width: 768px) {
  /* Styles specifically for mobile range */
}

/* Target mobile devices in portrait orientation */
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) and (orientation: portrait) {
  /* Portrait mobile styles */
}

/* Target mobile devices in landscape orientation */
@media screen and (max-width: 768px) and (orientation: landscape) {
  /* Landscape mobile styles */
}
```

**Mobile-first responsive approach:**
```css
/* Base styles (mobile-first) */
.container {
  width: 100%;
  padding: 15px;
}

/* Tablet and up */
@media screen and (min-width: 769px) {
  .container {
    width: 90%;
    padding: 20px;
  }
}

/* Desktop and up */
@media screen and (min-width: 1024px) {
  .container {
    width: 80%;
    max-width: 1200px;
    margin: 0 auto;
  }
}
```

The most commonly used mobile breakpoint is `max-width: 768px`, which covers most smartphones and small tablets.
